The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Calcutta, April 5: The tourism department today inked two agreements with private partners Emaar MGF and Sinclairs Hotels, which will invest Rs 2,200 crore over the next five years.          
	Realty major Emaar MGF Land Ltd has committed Rs 1,200 crore for three five-star luxury hotels in the city, a string of budget hotels and a resort in the Sunderbans. It will also invest Rs 800 crore to build integrated townships in the state. Sinclairs Hotels, a city-based company, has pledged Rs 200 crore in various projects, including a hotel management institute in Panagarh.                   
	New Delhi (PTI): BJP leader L.K. Advani on Saturday called veteran communist leader Satya Pal Dang in Amritsar over telephone and apologised for referring to him as late in his just-published autobiography.                  
	Lucknow ( PTI): The Uttar Pradesh government has banned opening of liquor shops in and around areas with Dalit population to prevent them from becoming alcoholics, an official said. It also forbids opening liquor shops within 50m of recognised, aided and government schools and charity-run places of worship following a Supreme Court order.                  
	 Calcutta: A fire broke out in a two-storey building on Canal West Road near Rajabazar on Saturday. The fire, which was noticed around 7.30pm, was probably caused by a short circuit in the ground floor that houses shops and other trading establishments.                  
	New Delhi (PTI): A Delhi court on Saturday reserved its order on the bail plea of arms dealer Suresh Nanda, his son and two others in a case of manipulating evidence on alleged kickbacks received in defence deals. The order is likely to come out on Sunday.                  
	Ajmer (PTI): A government college has withdrawn the compulsory dress code order for its staff following stiff opposition. The order, passed by the principal a few days ago, had made saree compulsory for women and trousers and shirt for men.                                                                                                                         
